\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces  Permutation throughput (99,999 permutations) across implementations on Apple M3 (8\,GB unified memory, 8 CPU cores). Log scale. Metal uses a stack-allocated scratchless shader at $n=49$, a single-pass uint32 index buffer for $n \leq 5{,}000$, and a batched fallback for $n=10{,}000$. Swift parallel (not shown) achieves 3.1M, 349k, 88k, 34k, 17k perm/s respectively. }}{1}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:throughput}{{1}{1}{}{figure.1}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces  Speedup relative to NumPy baseline (99,999 permutations). Swift+Metal achieves 77.8$\times $ at $n=49$ using the scratchless GPU shader, converging toward NumPy performance as $n$ grows and batch dispatch overhead dominates. Numba parallel provides consistent but modest speedup across all sizes. Swift CPU parallel (not shown) achieves 16.2$\times $ at $n=49$, declining to $\approx 3\times $ at $n \geq 500$ — consistently outperforming Numba at scale. }}{2}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:speedup}{{2}{2}{}{figure.2}{}}
